<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-550-752  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 550 752.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 11 1990 v9 n12 p35(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OPM's new software helps job seekers to FOCIS. (Office ofPersonnel Management's Federal Occupational and Career InformationSystem) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Federal Occupational and Career Information System (Utilityprogram) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionUnited States. Office of Personnel ManagementPersonnel ServicesCareer GuidanceInformation UtilitiesUtility Programs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>OPM's New Software Helps Job Seekers to FOCISandM;The Office of Personnel Management has developed software to help job seekersget detailed information about federal careers.andM;OPM software developers designed the MS-DOS package, called the FederalOccupational and Career Information System (FOCIS).andP;  The package offersinformation on more than 360 white-collar occupations, said Amiel Sharon,OPM's FOCIS project director.andM;It took a year for a team of OPM computer specialists and personnelspecialists to develop the system now available from the government, Sharonsaid.andP;  The developers wrote the code in Ashton-Tate Corp.'s dBase III Pluslanguage and compiled it in the Clipper application development system fromNantucket Corp. of Los Angeles, Sharon said.andM;FOCIS lists, under each occupation, descriptions of the work, minimumqualifications, grade levels, salaries and related college majors, Sharonsaid.andM;&quot;The package gives the entry-level salaries for each occupation, as well asthe average salaries and the grades of all people in those jobs,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;It also lists the agencies that hire for the various occupations.&quot;andM;FOCIS also includes information on the number of full-time employees bylocation and agency, as well as addresses to contact for employmentinformation.andP;  The package has descriptions and addresses of nearly 450federal organizations, agency officials said.andM;&quot;This new technology provides an effective way to enhance the federalgovernment's recruitment efforts and serves as a career guide to federalemployees.andP;  It also will help displaced employees learn about otheroccupations and provide a wealth of information to interested users,&quot; saidOPM Director Constance Berry Newman.andM;Agency officials projected that FOCIS users likely will include federalagencies, state employment services, colleges and universities, publiclibraries, federal employees and the public at large.andP;  The system will beupdated annually, agency officials said.andM;The menu-driven software comes on three floppy diskettes and runs on any IBMPC or compatible with a high-density disk drive.andP;  It requires MS-DOS 3.0 orgreater and 5M of hard drive space.andM;The package is $30 and includes the three diskettes, an installation guideand a user's guide.andM;To order, contact the National Technical Information Service, 5285 Port RoyalRoad, Springfield, Va.andP;  22161; tel.andP;  703-487-4650.andP;  The order number isPB90-501404.andO;</TEXT></DOC>